Headlines.SeoHeadline: High Times in Colorado? Not If You Want to Keep Your Job.
Headlines.Author: Melissa Korn
Headlines.Headline: High Times in Colorado? Not If You Want to Keep Your Job.

PARAGRAPH.#text: Recreational marijuana use will become legal in Colorado on Jan. 1, but workers might want to wait before lighting up at the office—or anywhere else.Employers can still set and enforce their own drug rules, according to state law. At some firms that might mean workers can't smoke pot on the premises; at others, they may not be able to smoke during down time, either, because of regular drug tests. The law, approved by voters in 2012, appeared to leave it to employers to decide whether to permit or forbid marijuana use by employees.Nevertheless, employers initially worried whether they could maintain their own drug policies, says Dick Mandelson, who heads up the employment law group at Baker & Hostetler LLP's Denver office.A closely-watched case a Colorado appellate court this spring ruled that employers are within their rights to fire workers who fail drug tests because they smoked pot, even if using the pot was legal. In that case, a quadriplegic who had a doctor's permission to use medical marijuana sued his employer, Dish Network, for firing him after he tested positive for the drug.The former Dish employee has filed an appeal; legal industry watchers predict more courtroom battles as recreational pot use becomes legal in some states.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: High Times in Colorado? Not If You Want to Keep Your Job.

PARAGRAPH.#text: Quest Diagnostics Inc.'s DGX second-quarter earnings fell 7% as revenue declined as consumers remained cautious about using health services. "We lowered our full-year revenue guidance to reflect softer healthcare utilization," said President and Chief Executive Steve Rusckowski. "Despite our reduced outlook for revenues, we maintained our EPS guidance within the previous range due to our confidence in our ability to deliver additional savings through our Invigorate initiative." For the year, the company lowered the high end of its per-share earnings estimate by a nickel and now expects $4.35 to $4.50 on a revenue decline of 1% to 2%.

Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Lower Taxes Lure More U.S. Firms Abroad

PARAGRAPH.#text: Politicians have been paying plenty of lip service to cutting corporate taxes in the U.S., but some companies are voting with their feet. Since 2009, at least 10 U.S. public companies have moved their incorporation address abroad or announced plans to do so -- up from just a handful from 2004 through 2008, the Journal's John D. Mackinnon and Scott Thurm report. Ensco International cut its effective tax rate to 10.5% in Q2, down from 19% in 2009, after moving from Dallas to the U.K. The savings: more than $100 million a year. The oil company was following in the footsteps of rivals Transocean, Noble and Weatherford International who were already taking advantage of more favorable tax rates overseas.

Headlines.Headline: MARKET TALK: Quest Diagnostics Shares Up on Merck News

PARAGRAPH.#text: 14:24 EDT - Goldman Sachs notes Quest Diagnostics (DGX) stands to benefit from Merck's (MRK) plan to close a clinical study of experimental osteoporosis drug odanacatib earlier than expected because of its success in preventing hip fractures. DGX holds mid- to high-single-digit royalties on future sales of the drug through 2023, Goldman says, which it estimates could raise per-share earnings as much as 39 cents at a 2017 peak. The firm believes investors have forgotten these and other royalties that DGX has held since last year's acquisition of Celera. DGX told Goldman it makes no assumptions on future royalties linked to Celera, but investors are sending shares of the diagnostic-testing company up 4.6% to $63.57 on heavy volume. (kristin.jones@dowjones.com)

Headlines.Author: Tess Stynes
Headlines.Headline: Quest Diagnostics To Complete Celera Deal Through Short-Form Merger

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Quest Diagnostics Inc. DGX plans to complete its deal for genetics-diagnostics test developer Celera Corp. CRA through a short-form merger, as the company announced that it held 61% of Celera's shares after the closing of tender offer, which had been extended several times. As of Tuesday's deadline about 53.2 million shares were tendered and not withdrawn, including 1.5 million tendered during the final one-week extension. Quest is the latest company to use a so-called "top up" option, which in this case allows the acquirer to purchase enough shares to give it a stake of more than 90% at the offer price of $8 each, allowing the company to complete the acquisition without a shareholder vote.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Quest Diagnostics To Complete Celera Deal Through Short-Form Merger

The diagnostic-testing company also said Monday it plans to buy back other shares owned by Glaxo that represent about a 9% stake in the company. Quest said it would pay for the repurchase with cash on hand and borrowing through available credit facilities. The repurchase will be applied against the company's current $1 billion share-repurchase authorization.

#text: Insurance company AFLAC

Analysts polled by First Call expected a profit of 32 cents a share. Revenue totaled $2.4 billion, less than 1 percent higher than the year-ago total. Net income totaled $17.5 million, an increase of 98 percent compared with last year. The company attributed the quarter's performance to continued strong demand for homes, especially in the first-time buyer segment. In addition, the company noted that demand fueled higher prices and the cost of construction dropped. Shares closed up $1.29 to $49.55 ahead of the news.

Headlines.Headline: Chinese-language U.S. apartment locator

#text:
As the proliferation of Internet access accelerates, users represent a broadening
    demographic group. To address this widening demand,

, an online apartment locator, recently
    allied with
North American

to provide Chinese-language services in the United States. Daniel Chiang,
    chairman and CEO of SINA, said in a press release, "SINANET.com now can give our huge
    population of Chinese Internet users the easiest, fastest and most convenient way to find
    a home -- online, and in their native language." Online users can virtually visit
    800,000 apartments in 41 states and Washington, D.C. The alliance has also produced a
    Chinese-language version of

, a
    site designed to facilitate relocation and moving.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Chinese-language U.S. apartment locator
